---
import BlogPostLayout from '../../layouts/BlogPostLayout.astro';
import { getBlogPost } from '../../lib/blog-posts';
import CodeBlock from '../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import ProbabilitySpace from '../../components/ProbabilitySpace';
import CloudShift from '../../components/CloudShift';
import TwoInputClouds from '../../components/TwoInputClouds';

export const frontmatter = {
  title: 'Probability Space Engineering',
  description:
    'A model call does not compute the answer. It materializes one sample from a possibility space fixed by your input and the model. Every prompting technique is one act: shaping that space until it lands on the solution.',
  author: 'Adelphi Liong',
  date: '2026-06-21',
  topic: 'tech' as const,
  tags: ['llm', 'ai', 'probability', 'prompt-engineering'],
  shareMessage: 'Every prompting trick is the same move: shaping a probability cloud onto the solution.',
};

const post = getBlogPost('probability-space-engineering')!;
---

<BlogPostLayout post={post}>
  <p class="mb-6">
    We talk about prompting as if it were instruction. You tell the model what to do, it does it, and
    if it does it badly you tell it more clearly. That framing is comfortable because it is how we talk
    to people. It is also wrong in a way that quietly caps how good you can get.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    A model does not receive an instruction and execute it. It receives a sequence of tokens and produces
    a distribution over what comes next, then samples from that distribution, then does it again. Nothing
    in that loop "decides" to give you the answer. The loop gives you <em>a</em> answer — one of many it
    could have given — and the set of answers it could have given is the real object you are working with.
    This post is about that object, what determines its shape, and the handful of operations that move it.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">Three regions</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Hold three things in mind at once. Call them regions of the same picture.
  </p>

  <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li>
      <strong>The solution space</strong> — the set of outputs you would actually accept. The correct
      function, the working migration, the answer that passes review. Often narrow. Sometimes a single point.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The possibility space</strong> — everything <em>this</em> input, run through <em>this</em>
      model, could produce. Not what it usually produces; what it <em>can</em>. Picture a cloud: dense in
      the middle, thinning at the edges, with a definite center of mass and a definite spread.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The materialization</strong> — one run. A single point sampled out of the cloud. It is the
      only part you ever actually see, which is exactly why the picture is so easy to miss.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Here is the move that makes the whole frame click. Run the same input three times. You get three
    different outputs. The naive reading is "the model is being random." The accurate reading is: the
    <em>possibility space was identical all three times</em> — same input, same model, same cloud — and
    you simply sampled a different point from it on each run. The variation between runs is not the model
    changing its mind. It is the cloud being sampled.
  </p>

  <ProbabilitySpace client:load />

  <p class="mb-6">
    This reframes what a "good run" is. A good run is not skill; it is a favorable sample. If you got a
    great answer once and a mediocre answer the next time, nothing about the model improved or degraded.
    The cloud stayed put. You just landed in a different part of it. Which means the lever that actually
    matters is not the individual sample — it is the <strong>shape and position of the cloud</strong>.
  </p>

  <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-primary pl-6 py-1 my-6 italic text-muted-foreground">
    The materialization is what you see. The possibility space is what you engineer. Confusing the two
    is the root of most prompting frustration.
  </blockquote>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">The job, geometrically</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Now overlay the two spaces. Most of the time, the possibility cloud does <em>not</em> sit on the
    solution. Its center of mass is somewhere nearby — plausible, confident, almost right — and the
    solution is off to one side. Sometimes the solution is inside the cloud but at a thin, low-probability
    edge, so you only hit it occasionally. Either way, the geometry tells you the whole job:
  </p>

  <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-primary pl-6 py-1 my-6 italic text-muted-foreground">
    Engineering an LLM is shifting the cloud onto the solution, and shrinking it so it stays there.
  </blockquote>

  <CloudShift client:load />

  <p class="mb-6">
    <strong>Shift</strong> moves the center of mass — toward the kind of answer you want. <strong>Shrink</strong>
    reduces the spread — so the answers you might get are all near the target instead of scattered across a
    wide neighborhood. Most techniques you already use do one, the other, or both. The trick is to stop
    naming them by their mechanics ("add few-shot examples," "use a reviewer") and start naming them by
    what they do to the cloud.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">A concrete handle</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Abstractions are cheap; here is one you can feel. Ask a model:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock lang="text" code={`Write me an algorithm in Ruby.`} />

  <p class="mb-6">
    The possibility space is enormous. It might give you a linear search, a binary search, a bubble sort,
    a quicksort, a graph traversal — all valid completions of that input. The cloud is broad because the
    input <em>permits</em> breadth. Now ask:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock lang="text" code={`Write me a binary search in Ruby.`} />

  <p class="mb-6">
    The cloud collapses. Almost every sample is now some variation of binary search. You did not make the
    model smarter. You handed it a tighter input, and a tighter input produces a tighter cloud. That is
    shrink, achieved purely through specificity.
  </p>

  <TwoInputClouds client:load />

  <p class="mb-6">
    This is why vague prompts feel unreliable and precise ones feel dependable. It is not reliability in
    any moral sense — it is variance. A broad cloud has high variance, so consecutive samples land far
    apart and the bad ones are common. A tight cloud has low variance, so even an unlucky sample is close
    to the target. "Be more specific" is not etiquette. It is variance reduction.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">The two knobs: input and model</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    The possibility space is a function of exactly two things: <strong>the input</strong> and
    <strong>the model</strong>. That is the whole equation. Everything you can do to change the output,
    you do by turning one of those two knobs.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    The input knob is the one you operate constantly — every word, every example, every file you put in
    context reshapes the cloud. The model knob is coarser but real: the <em>same input</em> lands on a
    different cloud depending on which model receives it. Give several models the bare prompt "write an
    algorithm in Ruby" and they don't just vary in quality — they vary in <em>where their cloud sits</em>:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="text"
    code={`Input: "write an algorithm in Ruby"   (illustrative tendencies)

  Model A   ->  tends to bubble sort        (teaches the classic example)
  Model B   ->  tends to quicksort          (reaches for the "real" one)
  Model C   ->  tends to binary search      (assumes "search" by default)
  Model D   ->  tends to linear search      (picks the simplest thing)

Same input. Four different centers of mass.`}
  />

  <p class="mb-6">
    The table is illustrative, not a benchmark — the point is the <em>shape</em> of the finding, which
    holds up whenever you measure it: identical inputs produce systematically different clouds across
    models. This is the
    <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/jagged-intelligence">jagged intelligence</a>
    surface, made concrete. The capability frontier is jagged — superb here, hopeless there, with no smooth
    slope between — and "where the cloud sits for a given input" is a way to actually <em>measure</em> that
    jaggedness instead of just describing it. The surface stops being a metaphor and becomes a coordinate
    you can read off.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">Context is a force, not free information</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Here is where the model overturns a habit almost everyone has. We treat context as additive: more
    context, more information, better answer. But context does not add information to a neutral container.
    Context <strong>is the input</strong>, and the input <em>is</em> what fixes the cloud. So every token
    you add is a force applied to the space — and forces have direction. Some of them push the cloud
    <em>away</em> from the solution.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Concretely, two failure modes:
  </p>

  <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li>
      <strong>Context rot.</strong> As a conversation grows long, the input is dominated by accumulated
      history — earlier attempts, dead ends, stale assumptions. The cloud drifts toward "more of this
      thread" and away from a clean solution. The model isn't getting tired; its input is getting heavy.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Context pollution.</strong> A single wrong fact, a misleading example, or a confident bad
      attempt earlier in the input drags the center of mass toward itself. One poisoned token can shift
      the whole cloud, and adding <em>more</em> context after it rarely pulls it back — it just adds noise
      around a center that is already in the wrong place.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p class="mb-6">
    This is precisely <em>why</em> a stateless, fresh-context loop works — the central move of the
    <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/autonomous-agents">autonomous agents</a> practice.
    If context is a force and a long thread pushes the cloud off-target, then the cure is not to argue the
    model back on course inside the same thread. The cure is to <em>discard the thread</em> and resample
    from a clean input. Statelessness isn't tidiness. It is refusing to let accumulated forces deform the
    space you are trying to aim.
  </p>

  <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-primary pl-6 py-1 my-6 italic text-muted-foreground">
    More context is not more information. It is a different cloud — sometimes a worse-placed one.
  </blockquote>

  <p class="mb-6">
    If you want the ground-level version of what "input" and "context" mean — the chat is just a view over
    a fixed token budget — that is the
    <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/how-llms-work">how LLMs actually work</a> primer.
    This post is what that primer is pointing at.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">The operations catalog</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Once you have the frame, the entire toolbox of "LLM techniques" stops being a list of tricks to memorize
    and becomes a small set of operations on the space. Each one does exactly one of three things: it
    <strong>shifts the cloud</strong>, it <strong>shrinks the cloud</strong>, or — the strongest move — it
    <strong>shrinks the solution space itself</strong>. Here is the catalog.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Fresh-context loops — resample from a clean space</h3>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Discard the current input and start over. When a run anchors on a bad approach, you cannot easily talk
    it out of the anchor, because the anchor <em>is part of the input</em> shaping the cloud. A fresh context
    resamples from a clean space that never had the anchor. It does not improve the model; it escapes a bad
    position. This is the loop from the agents post, viewed from the theory side.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Implementer + reviewer — a critique that shifts the cloud</h3>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Have one call produce an answer, a second call critique it, and a third call revise using the critique.
    The reviewer's output becomes an <em>intermediate input</em> to the revision — and a good critique points
    directly at the gap between where the cloud sits and where the solution is. So the revision's cloud is
    shifted toward the solution by exactly the vector the reviewer named. It is the same shape as a GAN:
    a generator and a discriminator, except the discriminator's signal is delivered as context rather than
    as a gradient.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Multi-reviewer — disjoint critiques that shrink the cloud</h3>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Add more reviewers, each watching a different axis — correctness, security, style, performance. Each
    disjoint critique constrains the revision along its own dimension, and constraints compound: the
    surviving cloud is the intersection of all of them, which is smaller than any single one. The catch is
    in the word <em>disjoint</em>. Two reviewers that watch the same axis don't intersect to anything new;
    they overlap, and overlap is diminishing returns. The value is in coverage, not headcount.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Lint / dead-code pre-filtering — fix the ratio before the reviewer</h3>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Run cheap deterministic filters — a linter, a dead-code pass, a compile check — to delete obviously bad
    candidates <em>before</em> a model reviewer ever sees them. The reviewer then judges a population that is
    already enriched for good candidates. You haven't made the reviewer smarter; you've improved the
    good-to-bad <em>ratio</em> of what it has to judge, which is often the cheaper win.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    There is a subtlety here worth naming — call it <strong>the Ioannidis problem</strong>, after the
    "why most published findings are false" argument. A filter with a fixed accuracy behaves
    <em>completely differently</em> at different base rates. Run a decent reviewer over a population that is
    mostly garbage and most of what it flags as "good" will still be garbage — false positives swamp true
    ones when good candidates are rare. The reviewer's quality is only half the story; the other half is the
    ratio of good to bad candidates flowing into it. Improving the ratio (pre-filtering) and improving the
    judge (better reviewer) are <em>both</em> levers, and ignoring the ratio is how good reviewers still
    produce bad pipelines.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Divide &amp; conquer — one prompt per item</h3>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Asking one broad prompt to handle ten things spreads the cloud thin across all of them; coverage on each
    individual item suffers because the space has to cover the union. Splitting into ten prompts — one per
    item — gives each its own tight, well-placed cloud. Narrower inputs, narrower clouds, better coverage. It
    is the specificity lever applied structurally rather than per-word.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Deterministic reduction — shrink the solution space itself</h3>

  <p class="mb-6">
    The strongest move, when it applies. Instead of asking the model to <em>do</em> the task, ask it to write
    a <strong>rule or a script</strong> that does the task — then run that script deterministically over every
    case. Every other operation in this catalog manipulates the <em>cloud</em>: shift it, shrink it, resample
    it. This one manipulates the <em>solution space</em>. A correct script doesn't sample an answer per case;
    it computes the same answer every time. You have collapsed the solution space to a point and removed the
    probabilistic layer entirely from the cases that follow.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="text"
    code={`Weak  : "rename every variable in these 400 files to camelCase"
        -> 400 samples from 400 clouds; a few will drift.

Strong: "write a codemod that renames snake_case to camelCase,
         then run it over all 400 files"
        -> one sampled artifact (the script), then 400 deterministic
           applications. No cloud per file.`}
  />

  <p class="mb-6">
    You still sample once — when the model writes the script. But you sample <em>once</em> for an artifact you
    can read, test, and reuse, instead of once per case for outputs you have to trust blind. Whenever a task
    can be reduced to a rule, reduce it. It is the difference between aiming a probabilistic process at every
    instance and aiming it a single time at the generator of a deterministic one.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">The callback</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Now turn back to the
    <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/autonomous-agents">autonomous agents</a> practice and
    read it again through this lens. Every move in it was probability-space engineering the whole time:
  </p>

  <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li>
      <strong>Declarative goals</strong> — writing the end-state instead of the keystrokes — is shrinking
      the cloud by making the input specific about the target rather than the path.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Stateless loops</strong> are fresh-context resampling: refusing to let an accumulated thread
      deform the space.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Looping</strong> instead of negotiating is buying more samples from a well-placed cloud rather
      than trying to argue a single sample into shape.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>A good spec</strong> — a sharp definition of "done" with a checkable definition of done — is
      doing both jobs at once: it shifts the cloud toward the target <em>and</em> shrinks the solution space
      to something you can actually verify a sample landed in.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p class="mb-6">
    None of those practices were arbitrary craft, and none of them were about treating the model like a junior
    teammate. They were all the same act, performed at different scales: take a possibility space fixed by your
    input and your model, and shift and shrink it until it sits on the solution. The practice is the theory,
    applied. Once you can see the cloud, you stop collecting techniques and start asking one question of every
    situation — <em>which way is the cloud off, and which operation moves it back?</em>
  </p>

  <div class="mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-border">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground mb-3">Related</p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-muted-foreground">
      <li>
        <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/autonomous-agents">Autonomous Agents</a> — the
        practice this theory explains
      </li>
      <li>
        <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/jagged-intelligence">Jagged Intelligence</a> — the
        surface, made measurable
      </li>
      <li>
        <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/how-llms-work">How LLMs Actually Work</a> — what
        "input" means
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</BlogPostLayout>
